Martial Artists are advanced unarmed fighters who synthesize Monk interior discipline with Brawler combat pragmatism.
The synthesis emerged in Kowloon's harbor districts where monastery lineages and pit fighting culture sustained contact.
Neither tradition could reliably defeat the other. Cross-training demonstrated superior performance against both.
Core integration: the Monk's Interior Forms applied to Brawler impact methodology produces qualitatively superior effects.
Combat role is sustained high-output melee with chi-enhanced strikes combining mechanical efficiency and internal energy.
The expanded chi capacity is a synergistic consequence, not a simple addition of both traditions.
Key abilities include chi techniques, breath control, structural timing, and full-contact combat endurance.
This is a remort class requiring effective apprenticeship in both Monk and Brawler traditions.
The first Martial Artists had completed two full apprenticeships before achieving the synthesis.
